tweets.text:
Just shipped our AI coding assistant to 1M developers.

Key insight from the rollout: the best AI tools don't replace developers, they amplify their intent.

Our users write 40% less code but build 60% more features.

The future of development is collaborative, not automated.

Thread on what I learned building AI systems at scale:

1/ The hardest part isn't the AI. It's the data.

95% of our engineering time goes into:
- Data validation
- Pipeline reliability
- Edge case handling
- Monitoring & observability

Only 5% is actual model work.

Unpopular opinion: Most companies don't need custom AI models.

They need:
- Better data infrastructure
- Clear use case definition
- Proper evaluation frameworks
- Change management processes

The model is often the easy part. Everything around it is hard.

We just open-sourced our AI safety evaluation toolkit.

2 years of work, now free for everyone.

Includes:
- Prompt injection detection
- Output validation frameworks
- Red-teaming templates
- Bias evaluation metrics

Link: github.com/safetylabs/eval-toolkit

RT to spread the word

Hot take: In 2025, the most valuable AI skill isn't prompt engineering.

It's knowing when NOT to use AI.

Seen too many teams:
- Overcomplicate simple problems
- Add latency to critical paths
- Create maintenance nightmares

Sometimes a regex is all you need.
